  <div id="grooming" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Grooming the Teddy-Bear Coat in Our Humid Climate" imageAlt="Cavapoochon puppy having its soft teddy-bear coat brushed during grooming" imageSrc={cavapoochonGrooming} imagePosition="left">
      <p>The Cavapoochon's coat is the densest of our poodle crosses: soft, rounded, and low-shedding, which means the loose hair stays in the coat until you brush it out. Brush 3 to 4 times a week to prevent matting, and book professional grooming every 6 to 8 weeks. Singapore's humidity speeds up matting, so a consistent routine matters more here than in cooler climates.</p>
      <p>Keep the teddy trim short and the routine stays easy; let the coat grow long and the brushing becomes a daily job. Light tear staining can show on cream faces; a daily wipe with clean water keeps it in check, and the tools you need are already in the starter kit.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>

  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" />
  <div id="health" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Cavapoochon Health: What We Check Before You Take One Home" imageAlt="Cavapoochon puppy at a veterinary health check before going home" imageSrc={cavapoochonVet} variant="mid">
      <p>Every Cavapoochon goes home vet-checked, vaccinated, dewormed, and microchipped. The health points worth knowing: patellar luxation, a kneecap issue common to small breeds; dental crowding, so the oral care items in your kit matter; and floppy-ear hygiene, since covered ears in a humid climate need a regular check and wipe. One more, said plainly because honest sellers should: the Cavalier line carries heart-health history, so ask any seller, us included, about the parents. We'll answer straight.</p>
      <p>Feeding is simple: your puppy comes with the small-breed food it is already eating, and any change should be gradual over a week. For portioning guidance see the <a href="/learn/puppy-health" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">puppy health checks explained</a> guide.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>
  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" flip />

  <CaptionedBlock heading="Your Cavapoochon's First Week at Home" imageAlt="Cavapoochon puppy settling into a set-up playpen during its first week home" imageSrc={cavapoochonSettling} imagePosition="left">
    <p>Day 0: we deliver, free, at a time that suits you, usually morning or evening. The playpen, bed, water, and toys are set up before your Cavapoochon explores the room, and we walk you through all 30+ starter-kit items in person. Learn more about <a href="/delivery" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">how our free home delivery and setup works</a>.</p>
    <p>Days 1 to 3: keep it calm and close. Cavapoochons settle fast with gentle company nearby, a fixed feeding routine, and the toilet pads where we placed them. Some night whimpering is normal adjustment.</p>
    <p>Days 4 to 7: the routine sticks. This is the window to book your free first lesson with an AVS-certified trainer; see <a href="/free-training" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">what the free AVS-certified training lesson covers</a>. For anything in between, you WhatsApp us.</p>
  </CaptionedBlock>

